<subSubSection id="17F3652CFFFFD46BB622F73BFBE7B018" pageId="3" pageNumber="128" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph id="5F5636A7FFFFD46BB622F73BFBF9BF60" blockId="3.[810,1420,1639,1875]" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">
<emphasis id="6D9DEAB5FFFFD46BB622F73BFB8FBE4C" bold="true" box="[810,1028,1639,1663]" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">Material captured.</emphasis>
One male (
<collectionCode id="39F8AE62FFFFD46BB18AF73BFB47BE4C" box="[1154,1228,1639,1663]" country="Ecuador" httpUri="http://grbio.org/cool/kwpg-nhbg" name="Museo de Zoologia, Pontificia Universidad Catolica del Ecuador" pageId="3" pageNumber="128" type="Museum">QCAZ</collectionCode>
17930), measurements (in mm): total 222, ear 22, foot 30; 
<geoCoordinate id="3ADD5060FFFFD46BB1DEF7D5FADABE91" box="[1238,1361,1673,1698]" degrees="03" direction="south" minutes="03" orientation="latitude" pageId="3" pageNumber="128" precision="15" seconds="37" value="-3.0602777">03°03′37″S</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate id="3ADD5060FFFFD46BB051F7D7FC02BEF6" degrees="079" direction="west" minutes="13" orientation="longitude" pageId="3" pageNumber="128" precision="15" seconds="40" value="-79.227776">079° 13′40″W</geoCoordinate>
; elevation 
<quantity id="98119B42FFFFD46BB104F7F2FBE5BEF6" box="[1036,1134,1710,1734]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.807" pageId="3" pageNumber="128" unit="m" value="3807.0">3,807 m</quantity>
; 
<date id="2B571067FFFFD46BB189F7F2FABBBEF5" box="[1153,1328,1710,1734]" pageId="3" pageNumber="128" value="2018-08-09">9 August 2018</date>
; collec- tors: Lee, Tinoco and Crockett collected this specimen in a paramo bog. Two skulls (
<collectionCode id="39F8AE62FFFFD46BB19BF7A8FB56BF3F" box="[1171,1245,1780,1804]" country="Ecuador" httpUri="http://grbio.org/cool/kwpg-nhbg" name="Museo de Zoologia, Pontificia Universidad Catolica del Ecuador" pageId="3" pageNumber="128" type="Museum">QCAZ</collectionCode>
1940-41) were found in owl pellets in a paramo cliff face (
<geoCoordinate id="3ADD5060FFFFD46BB005F64AFA0CBF1C" box="[1293,1415,1814,1839]" degrees="03" direction="south" minutes="03" orientation="latitude" pageId="3" pageNumber="128" precision="15" seconds="32" value="-3.058889">03°03′32″S</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate id="3ADD5060FFFFD46BB622F665FC36BF61" box="[810,957,1849,1874]" degrees="079" direction="west" minutes="13" orientation="longitude" pageId="3" pageNumber="128" precision="15" seconds="06" value="-79.21833">079°13′06″W</geoCoordinate>
); 
<date id="2B571067FFFFD46BB6D8F667FBE5BF60" box="[976,1134,1851,1875]" pageId="3" pageNumber="128" value="2018-08-03">3 August 2018</date>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5F5636A7FFFFD46BB622F63FFBE7B018" blockId="3.[810,1420,1891,2091]" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">
<emphasis id="6D9DEAB5FFFFD46BB622F63FFC40BF48" bold="true" box="[810,971,1891,1915]" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">Identification.</emphasis>
The dorsum is orange brown and washed with black. The base of the dorsal fur is dark gray (
<figureCitation id="C7D22A22FFFFD46BB069F6DAFCC5BFF2" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="3.[168,231,1575,1595]" captionTargetBox="[168,778,160,1551]" captionTargetId="figure-518@3.[168,778,160,1551]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figure 2. Mammals of Quimsacocha National Recreation Area, Azuay Province, Ecuador. A. Caenolestes caniventer. B. Didelphis pernigra. C. Cryptotis montivagus. D. Akodon mollis. E. Microryzomys latissimus. F. Phyllotis haggard. G. Sigmodon inopinatus. H. Coendou rufescens. I. Odocoileus virginianus ustus. J. Sylvilagus andinus." pageId="3" pageNumber="128">Fig. 2G</figureCitation>
). The ventral fur is light gray (
<bibRefCitation id="3B784B56FFFFD46BB192F6F5FA93BFF2" author="Tirira DS" box="[1178,1304,1961,1985]" pageId="3" pageNumber="128" refId="ref5785" refString="Tirira DS (2017) A field guide to the mammals of Ecuador. 1 st English edition. Publicacion Especial Sobre los Mamiferos del Ecuador 10. Blanco, Quito, Ecuador, 600 pp" type="book" year="2017">Tirira 2017</bibRefCitation>
). Short nasals, long incisive foramina, small auditory bullae and a narrow interorbital region distinguish this species from other 
<taxonomicName id="98E94D24FFFFD46BB660F94FFBECB018" authority="(Voss 2015 a)" baseAuthorityName="Voss" baseAuthorityYear="2015" box="[872,1127,2067,2091]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Sigmodon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="3" pageNumber="128" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="6D9DEAB5FFFFD46BB660F94FFC5FB018" box="[872,980,2067,2091]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">Sigmodon</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="3B784B56FFFFD46BB6EAF94FFBEBB018" author="Voss RS" box="[994,1120,2067,2091]" pageId="3" pageNumber="128" pagination="566 - 571" refId="ref5821" refString="Voss RS (2015 a) Tribe Sigmodontini Wagner, 1843. In: Patton JL, Pardinas UFJ, D'Elia G (Eds.) Mammals of South America Vol. 2. (J. The University of Chicago Press, Chicago, USA, 566 - 571." type="book chapter" year="2015">Voss 2015a</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
